<h1>
java - Servlet path "/" returns that servlet content for any request pattern - Stack Overflow
<\h1>
<p>When I map servlet with path as like:</p>
<pre><code>&lt;servlet&gt;
    &lt;servlet-name&gt;Home1Servlet&lt;/servlet-name&gt;
    &lt;servlet-class&gt;com.project.servlets.Home1Servlet&lt;/servlet-class&gt;
&lt;/servlet&gt;
&lt;servlet-mapping&gt;
    &lt;servlet-name&gt;Home1Servlet&lt;/servlet-name&gt;
    &lt;url-pattern&gt;/&lt;/url-pattern&gt;
&lt;/servlet-mapping&gt;
</code></pre>
<p>And then when I request servlet from browser by any paths like:</p>
<pre><code>http://localhost:8084/project/
http://localhost:8084/project/asd
http://localhost:8084/project/why
http://localhost:8084/project/hell
</code></pre>
<p>All these requests return same Home1Servlet content. Why?</p>
<p>How can map servlet only to path "/"?</p>
<p>I am using Apache Tomcat 6.0.26, Java EE 5. Context path is: /project</p>
<p>If you want to map servlet ONLY to root url then use empty mapping:</p>
<pre><code>&lt;url-pattern&gt;&lt;/url-pattern&gt;
</code></pre>
<p>It's described in Servlet specification 12.2:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The empty string ("") is a special URL pattern that exactly maps to
  the application's context root, that is, requests of the form
  host:port/&lt;context_root&gt;/. In this case the path info is  /  and
  the servlet path and context path is empty string ("").</p>
</blockquote>